^b@2^*bColor Definitions^*n     Page 2  

Color definitions, are commonly put at the start of the lin file with the fonts. They consist of a set of commands normally all written on one line. For example @- 

^d  cr!|cp|7|at|^*b7^*n|cp||at|255!   cb!|cp|7|at|^*b7^*n|cp||at|0!   cg!|cp|7|at|^*b7^*n|cp||at|0!                  (it is safe to add a comment here, like @-)    7 red

The above is a definition for   Color |cp|7|at|^*b7^*n|cp||at|  there can be up to a maxium of 9 colors numbered from  1 to 9.

                                                                    ^d since ^*b aaBridge ^*n build |cp|blue|at|^*b2814^*n|cp||cs|mu|at|  there are { an ADDITIONAL  26 configurable colors }  ^*b a - z ^*n   eg.   !cg!|cp|7|at|^*bk^*n|cp||at|255!
																	
^c !cr!|cp|7|at|^*b7^*n|cp||at|255!    ^gRed component      @-  255

^c !cg!|cp|7|at|^*b7^*n|cp||at|0!    ^gGreen component   @-  0

^c !cb!|cp|7|at|^*b7^*n|cp||at|0!    ^gBlue component      @-  0

While, unlike fonts, you can change the values of colors in the middle of the file. However, I recommend you keep these numbered colors at the same color value through out your lin file.  You will find life simpler that way.


^b@2^*bUsing the Color^*n^z@3|
at|

You switch to using the color  |cp|7|at|^*b7^*n|cp||at|  with the command     !cp!|cp|7|at|^*b7^*n|cp||at|!     while     !cp!!    will restore the default of black.

All the red |cp|7|at|^*b7^*n|cp||at|'s on this page are being displayed using this color definition.

There is also the  !cs!|cp|7|at|^*b7^*n|cp||at|!   command that sets the fill color of any boxes you create, |cs|7|at| covered { later }.   !cs!!  restores this fill color to the default background.

	^*b In-Color Comment ^*n   -   You can add a  HYPHEN  and then a comment when USING a color   eg.     !cp!|cp|7|at|^*b7^*n|cp||at|-red!

